            <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/recess/culture/music">CULTURE MUSIC</a></span></div>

                <h1>Miguel Zenon fuses Puerto Rican heritage with American jazz</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/55bc75f1-0e72-4735-aed7-f02efb724223.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="" class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            

                            
                        </div>
                    </figure>
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/andrew-hibbard">Andrew Hibbard</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">February 11, 2010 | 5:00am EST</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2010/02/miguel-zenon-fuses-puerto-rican-heritage-american-jazz" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2010/02/miguel-zenon-fuses-puerto-rican-heritage-american-jazz&amp;text=Miguel Zenon fuses Puerto Rican heritage with American jazz" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Miguel%20Zenon%20fuses%20Puerto%20Rican%20heritage%20with%20American%20jazz%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2010%2F02%2Fmiguel-zenon-fuses-puerto-rican-heritage-american-jazz" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p><em>Saxophonist Miguel Zenon is kicking off Duke Performances&rsquo; mini jazz festival WAIL! tonight. The Puerto Rican musician, now living in New York, recently ended a sensational decade that in 2008 alone saw him awarded both a Guggenheim Fellowship and a MacArthur &ldquo;genius&rdquo; grant. Zenon will be bringing the result of some of that work to Duke tonight with the Esta Plena Septet. Consisting of his jazz quartet and three purveyors of Puerto Rican plena music, the project is a post-modern fusion of classic jazz with Afro-Caribbean folk music. Andrew Hibbard spoke to Zenon about the project, his influences and more. </em></p>
<p><strong>What sparked your interest in plena music for the Esta Plena project?</strong></p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>I&rsquo;ve been listening to plena since I was a kid. I grew up around it. It&rsquo;s a pretty common style of music to hear if you live in Puerto Rico, but I would say within the last few years, I started getting more and more interested in it&mdash;specifically the history and development of the style. The times I got to visit Puerto Rico I found the music was omnipresent, and I was really interested in the protagonism the music had in this everyday culture. So that was what drew me to pursue this investigation and the project itself.</p>
<p><strong>How did you end up getting into jazz given Puerto Rico&rsquo;s soundscape?</strong></p>
<p>There wasn&rsquo;t that much jazz in Puerto Rico when I was growing up. There actually isn&rsquo;t that much jazz now. I went to a music school when I was growing up there, from around age 11 to age 17. It was mainly classical training with a little popular music here and there. I discovered jazz while at school through some friends listening to recordings and all that. What initially drew my attention to the style was the improvisation aspect to the music. Since I was trained in classical music, that aspect wasn&rsquo;t present.</p>
<p><strong>What has sustained this interest over the years? </strong></p>
<p>Of course as I got more and more into the music, I found that improvisation is not found only in jazz, it&rsquo;s found in all kinds of music. But it wasn&rsquo;t improvisation all by itself. It was a language that was tied to a history and to a development throughout the years. After I discovered that, I put all my focus in studying the history of jazz and the history of my instrument, in order to just fill all the holes I needed to grow as a jazz musician. This is stuff I still do. It&rsquo;s not just something you do very quickly.</p>
<p><strong>How did you approach bridging plena music and jazz? </strong></p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>I&rsquo;ve dealt with the idea, not with plena before, but with trying to fuse some elements of Puerto Rican or Caribbean or Latin American music. But specifically on this recording, it was the first recording I was bringing the traditional instruments of the style to. In this case, the hand percussion that is symbolic of the style&mdash;the bandero, it&rsquo;s at the heart of it. I brought those instruments and I include some lyrics in some of the songs. The idea was to have two worlds. You have the jazz world, which is represented by the quartet&mdash;saxophone, bass, piano, drums&mdash;and you have the more folkloric plena world, which is represented by the lyrics and the bandero. When I wrote the music, the idea was for these two worlds to coexist with each other, moving parallel but without compromising the essential elements of each style. We&rsquo;re still playing with a jazz conception in mind, but rhythmically we are living within a corollary that comes from within plena. But I still see it as a jazz record.</p>
<p><strong>Were there any difficulties for your quartet in adapting to the plena musicians? 
</strong></p>
<p>It was pretty easy. I&rsquo;ve been working with these guys for a long time. With the percussionists, I knew them too. I was very careful and conscious of wanting to make everyone feel as comfortable as possible, and I wanted everyone to be able to feel they could play the music to the best of their ability. So when I wrote the music, I was thinking that I didn&rsquo;t want the guys playing percussion to have something weird they&rsquo;d have to adapt to. The music was written around the rhythms they played. They just played the way they play, and the music that we played was built on top of that.&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Given your already global focus, how did your tour of West Africa in 2003 contribute to your musical development?</strong></p>
                            

<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="fdab49f43c">
    <h3>Get The Dirt</h3>
    <p>Subscribe to our weekly email about what&#039;s trending at Duke</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=fdab49f43c" method="post">
                <div class="input-group">
                    <input type="email" name="EMAIL" class="form-control form-control-sm" placeholder="Your email address" />
