                    <div class="input-group-append">
                        <input type="submit" value="Subscribe" class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm sends-events" data-ga-category="CTA" data-ga-action="email_focus" data-ga-label="fdab49f43c" />
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div style="position: absolute; left: -5000px;"><input type="text" name="b_c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b_fdab49f43c" tabindex="-1" value=""></div>

            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>A lot of the music we play in America is directly connected to the music we brought over from Africa 500 years ago. But the thing that I found when I went over there&mdash;I kind of knew this already&mdash;but what hit me in the face was how I was able to see all this stuff from the roots. We visited Nigeria, Congo, Cameroon, a lot of places that have a strong connection to the music we play in America. A lot of the rhythms we&rsquo;re playing, people related to immediately. Even some of the Puerto Rican or Caribbean rhythms we play, they would have the same rhythms with a different name there. They related to it like it was their music. It made me see things in a different way&mdash;not necessarily Puerto Rican, Cuban or American music. It&rsquo;s all kind of connected, and it&rsquo;s all variations on the same root.</p>
<p><strong>What do you make of your explosion of success and popularity over the past 10 years?</strong></p>
<p>For me, it&rsquo;s a whole different perspective. I guess what you&rsquo;re talking about is a certain measure of success that&rsquo;s hard for me to measure. What&rsquo;s really helped me is that I&rsquo;ve been able to be in contact with a lot of important figures in the style of music I&rsquo;ve been working on. I&rsquo;ve been able to play with a lot of legendary musicians, and share the stage with a lot of great musicians. This has put me in some sort of limelight but prepared me to be a better musician, better leader. A lot of other things have happened like the Guggenheim and the MacArthur [fellowships]. The combination of all those other things have helped. I honestly feel these are opportunities that have been presented to me that could have been presented to anyone. I did my best to prepare for when these opportunities arrived, and I feel that this preparation and trying to be focused and be at my best, this is what helped me the most.</p>
<p><strong>What are your thoughts on playing in Durham?</strong></p>
<p>I&rsquo;m really looking forward to it. Whenever I talk to anyone from there, I always say the same thing and it&rsquo;s that I happen to be a really big fan of the Blue Devils and I&rsquo;ve been trying to get some tickets for a while. But I&rsquo;ll be rooting for them, and I&rsquo;m looking forward to playing there because I&rsquo;ve never played [at Duke] before and I&rsquo;m excited to be close to the team.</p>
<p><em>Miguel Zenon will perform tonight in Reynolds Industries Theater at 8 p.m. Tickets are $22-28 or $5 for students</em></p>

